{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"475f4734-96eb-4f44-9808-25ca5e40a139","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9.0**, so you have the modern APIs available.\n\n**Recommended pattern:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via **constructor parameter** (MSTest v3+).\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor itself.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task`.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor runs first (sync), then `[TestInitialize]` runs (supports `async Task`).\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property approach still works but constructor injection is cleaner in v3+.\n- Use `[TestCleanup]` (also supports `async Task`) for teardown.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a6d62f2-cb88-4c2a-9730-9a1f7e6271c5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type (supported in MSTest v2+).\n\nLet me give them a clear, concise answer about the modern MSTest approach.\n\n\nWith MSTest 3.x, I can inject `TestContext` directly through a constructor parameter, and I can mix synchronous initialization in the constructor with asynchronous setup in a `[TestInitialize]` method that returns `async Task`.","outputTokens":569,"requestId":"4818:2AD648:888B04:9D13A3:69FBEB5A"},"id":"9b37ce58-94e2-4b43-918e-7468440a45f4","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:31:18.011Z","parentId":"acee6772-3657-4d64-aac4-98f46544eaa4"}
